Introduction :¶

Cryptocurrencies have revolutionized the financial landscape, presenting unique opportunities and challenges in the domain of investment and trading. Their decentralized nature, combined with high volatility, makes predicting market trends both a significant challenge and an opportunity for innovation. Leveraging machine learning, we aim to address the critical question of whether a cryptocurrency's price will rise or fall on a given day based on historical market data.

As engineering students from the 23rd batch of the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Ruhuna, Pasan and I, Nimesh, undertook this project as part of our fifth-semester coursework in Machine Learning. Together, we focused on developing a predictive model for trend analysis in the cryptocurrency market. By analyzing features such as open price, close price, highest and lowest prices, market capitalization, and market volume from daily historical data dating back to 2013, our model identifies price movement trends.

Using supervised learning algorithms, specifically the Random Forest Classifier and Support Vector Machine (SVM), we aim to classify the trend direction—upward or downward. This project not only explores the integration of machine learning in financial markets but also enhances our understanding of data-driven decision-making and predictive analytics in real-world applications.

Literature Review :¶

Cryptocurrency markets have emerged as a dynamic and rapidly evolving financial domain. Their decentralized and volatile nature has attracted researchers to explore innovative methods for analyzing and predicting market trends. Machine learning (ML) techniques have become prominent in this regard, offering robust tools for handling large datasets and uncovering patterns that are not readily apparent through traditional analytical methods.

Predictive Analysis in Financial Markets Predictive modeling in financial markets has historically relied on statistical methods. However, machine learning has enabled more sophisticated approaches, allowing for the integration of diverse data sources and the identification of complex, non-linear relationships. Research by Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated the effectiveness of machine learning algorithms like Random Forest and Support Vector Machines in stock market predictions, emphasizing their capability to outperform traditional models in accuracy and efficiency.

Cryptocurrencies and Machine Learning The unique attributes of cryptocurrencies—such as high volatility, 24/7 trading, and sensitivity to global events—make them a challenging but attractive target for ML-based prediction. Studies such as those by McNally et al. (2018) highlight the application of ML for predicting Bitcoin prices, utilizing algorithms like Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks for time-series forecasting. Their work underscores the potential of ML in achieving accurate short-term predictions.

Challenges in Cryptocurrency Trend Analysis Despite the progress, challenges remain in accurately predicting cryptocurrency price trends. High market volatility, sudden price shocks, and the influence of external factors like regulatory news or social media sentiment often introduce noise into the data. This necessitates the use of robust preprocessing techniques and the adoption of algorithms capable of handling uncertainty and noise.

Dataset Description :¶

The dataset used for this project is sourced from Kaggle and contains historical price information for Bitcoin (Cryptocurrency Historical Prices https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sudalairajkumar/cryptocurrencypricehistory/data), one of the most prominent cryptocurrencies. This dataset offers daily price data starting from April 28, 2013, including key features such as opening price, closing price, highest and lowest prices, market capitalization, and transaction volume. These parameters provide a comprehensive view of Bitcoin's market behavior, enabling a data-driven approach to trend prediction.

For this project, we specifically focused on Bitcoin's data due to its significance in the cryptocurrency market and the availability of a rich historical dataset. The target variable, trend direction (upward or downward), was derived by comparing the opening and closing prices of each day. This dataset serves as an excellent foundation for applying supervised learning algorithms to analyze and predict market trends, addressing key questions about Bitcoin's price movements and their underlying factors.

The data was collected from CoinMarketCap and is openly available for research purposes, making it an ideal choice for machine learning-based cryptocurrency market analysis.

In [9]:
#Define the Trend column for the current day based on the relationship between Open and Close prices
df['Trend'] = np.where(df['Close'] > df['Open'], 'Up', 'Down')

# Shift the Trend column up by one to make it represent the next day's trend
df['Next_Day_Trend'] = df['Trend'].shift(-1)

# Drop the last row as it will have NaN in Next_Day_Trend
df = df.dropna(subset=['Next_Day_Trend'])

# Define the percentage split for train and test sets (e.g., 70% train, 30% test)
train_percentage = 0.7

# Calculate the split index
split_index = int(len(df) * train_percentage)

# Create train and test sets
x_train = x.iloc[:split_index]  # First 70% of the data for training
y_train = y.iloc[:split_index]  # First 70% of the target for training

x_test = x.iloc[split_index:]  # Remaining 30% of the data for testing
y_test = y.iloc[split_index:]  # Remaining 30% of the target for testing

# Print the sizes of the train and test sets
print("Train set size (x_train, y_train):", x_train.shape, y_train.shape)
print("Test set size (x_test, y_test):", x_test.shape, y_test.shape)

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, precision_score

# Predictions for training and test sets
train_pred = baseModel.predict(x_train)
test_pred = baseModel.predict(x_test)

# Evaluation metrics for the training set
train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, train_pred)
train_confusion = confusion_matrix(y_train, train_pred)
train_precision = precision_score(y_train, train_pred)

# Evaluation metrics for the test set
test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, test_pred)
test_confusion = confusion_matrix(y_test, test_pred)
test_precision = precision_score(y_test, test_pred)

# Print results
print("Training Set Metrics:")
print(f"Accuracy: {train_accuracy}")
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(train_confusion)
print(f"Precision: {train_precision}\n")

print("Test Set Metrics:")
print(f"Accuracy: {test_accuracy}")
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(test_confusion)
print(f"Precision: {test_precision}")

param_dist = {
    'n_estimators': np.arange(100, 500, 50),

Model Evaluation and Discussion¶

Features of our dataframe indicates a correlation close to zero with the target variable "Next_Day_Trend", but highly correlated with each other. So some features were droped. But as a feature engineering, new features were added using close price feature such as 50 day moving average and price changing precentage. Also lag data was added since this is time series datafram. Another feature was added deu to BTC' harving cycles called"Cycle_Year". They also indicates a correlation close to zero with the target variable "Next_Day_Trend". How ever null values, duplicate values and out liers were checked. Only first 50 rows had the Null values so they were romoved. Since outliers do not effect to this model "RandomForestClassifier", they were not consider so much. Before train the model target value count was checked, its show some balance Next_Day_Trend and assumed that RandomForestClassifier model can hadle this much imbalance.

How ever initialy got result as Trainning Accuracy: 0.8726919339164237 and Test Accuracy: 0.4971687429218573. It shows model is overfitting. When hyperparameter tunning for increase accuracy model was able to get much more accuracy to predict Ture values as Training Precision: 0.7272, Test Precision: 0.6667 while whole model is overfitting. So this is happenning due to imbalance of the data, so classification_report and roc_auc_score used to evaluate classification model on imbalance data set. An ROC-AUC score of 0.5080 was indicated on our model. This means the model performing only slightly better than random guessing in distinguishing between the two classes.

from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix, roc_auc_score
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from imblearn.pipeline import Pipeline

# 1. Oversampling the Minority Class
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)

# 2. Class Weight Adjustment and Scaling
scaler = StandardScaler()
svm_model = SVC(kernel='rbf', random_state=42, class_weight='balanced')

# 3. Pipeline for preprocessing and modeling
pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('smote', smote),
    ('scaler', scaler),
    ('svm', svm_model)
])

# Parameter distributions for hyperparameter tuning
param_distributions = {
    'svm__C': [0.1, 1, 10, 100],
    'svm__gamma': [1, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001]
}

# Initialize RandomizedSearchCV
random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=pipeline,
    param_distributions=param_distributions,
    n_iter=10,
    cv=5,
    scoring='roc_auc',
    verbose=2,
    random_state=42,
    n_jobs=-1
)

# Train on balanced data
random_search.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Best model
best_pipeline = random_search.best_estimator_

# Predictions
y_train_pred = best_pipeline.predict(x_train)
y_test_pred = best_pipeline.predict(x_test)

# Metrics
train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
train_precision = precision_score(y_train, y_train_pred, pos_label=1)
test_precision = precision_score(y_test, y_test_pred, pos_label=1)
train_recall = recall_score(y_train, y_train_pred, pos_label=1)
test_recall = recall_score(y_test, y_test_pred, pos_label=1)
train_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_train, best_pipeline.decision_function(x_train))
test_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, best_pipeline.decision_function(x_test))

print("Best Parameters:", random_search.best_params_)
print("\n--- Train Metrics ---")
print(f"Accuracy: {train_accuracy:.4f}, Precision: {train_precision:.4f}, Recall: {train_recall:.4f}, ROC-AUC: {train_roc_auc:.4f}")
print("\n--- Test Metrics ---")
print(f"Accuracy: {test_accuracy:.4f}, Precision: {test_precision:.4f}, Recall: {test_recall:.4f}, ROC-AUC: {test_roc_auc:.4f}")
print("\nConfusion Matrix (Train):\n", confusion_matrix(y_train, y_train_pred))
print("\nConfusion Matrix (Test):\n", confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred))
print("\nClassification Report (Test):\n", classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))

Model Evaluation and Discussion¶

Due to SVM highly effected in value sizes and outliers, in biginning Standardization (Z-Score Scaling) was done to the previous training and test tests.

The evaluation of the SVM model revealed significant challenges due to class imbalance in the dataset, leading to poor performance on the minority class (0). Pre-tuning accuracy was 52.4%, with the model heavily biased toward predicting the majority class (1), achieving high recall (92%) for this class but near-zero recall for the minority class. Hyperparameter tuning marginally improved test accuracy to 54.5%, but the model still struggled with the minority class, as reflected in the confusion matrices and classification reports.

To handle the class imbalance and improve the model's performance an approach, oversampling was done to the minority Class using SMOTE. Classification_report and roc_auc_score used to evaluate classification model on imbalance data set. An ROC-AUC score of 0.4708 was indicated on our model. This means the model performing pooor in distinguishing between the two classes.

Conclusion¶

Both the Random Forest and SVM models faced significant challenges in predicting the target variable "Next_Day_Trend" due to class imbalance and weak correlation between the features and the target. The Random Forest model exhibited severe overfitting, achieving high training accuracy (87.27%) but low test accuracy (49.72%), with an ROC-AUC score of 0.5080, indicating performance only slightly better than random guessing. Similarly, the SVM model struggled with class imbalance, achieving near-zero recall for the minority class pre-tuning and marginal improvements post-SMOTE, with an ROC-AUC score of 0.4708. Both models highlighted the need for better class balancing techniques, feature engineering, and alternative algorithms. Future efforts should focus on addressing these issues through resampling methods, exploring domain-specific features, and testing robust models like Gradient Boosting or class-weighted algorithms to improve performance on this challenging dataset.
